# Agnostic Language Server — Thesis Authoring

## Source Hierarchy

When writing or revising ALS content, treat sources in this order (most to least authoritative):

1. **Haskell library (canonical)** — `/Users/kf/Documents/projects/uni/free-foil-ls/src/`
   - Entry point / re-export facade: `AgnosticLanguageServer.hs`
   - Core modules: `AgnosticLanguageServer/{AST,Cache,Classes,Common,Types}.hs`
   - Handlers: `AgnosticLanguageServer/Handlers/{Definition,Diagnostics,Hover,Rename,SemanticTokens,Sync}.hs`
2. **Example consumer (reference only)** — `/Users/kf/Documents/projects/uni/free-foil-ls/flan-language-server/src/LanguageServer/AgnosticLanguageServerFlan.hs` — a complete language server built *on top of* the library; not part of the library itself
3. **Russian paper** — `.cursor/als_ru.md` — latest design decisions; concise global overview
4. **Thesis text** — least authoritative; may lag behind or contain errors

If sources disagree, follow the `free-foil-ls` library source. Use the Russian paper for structure and high-level design intent. Treat existing thesis prose as draft until verified against Haskell.

Use `AgnosticLanguageServerFlan.hs` to understand how a consumer wires the library together, but do not present Flan code as library internals.

