## Haskell Snippets in Prose

When quoting or adapting code for the thesis, **strip import aliases** for readability:

```haskell
-- In source:  F.Name, F.Scope, F.AST, Map.fromList, T.pack
-- In thesis:  Name, Scope, AST, fromList, pack
```

Common aliases to omit: `F` (Foil/Free-Foil), `Map`, `T` (Text), `LSP`, `R` (generated parser modules in the example).

Keep types, class names, and logic faithful to the implementation; only simplify qualified names.

### Snippet layout and line breaks

Thesis code snippets use a **serif font**, not monospaced. Format for readability in that context:

- **Line width:** keep every line **under 80 characters**. Break long lines rather than letting them run wide.
- **No column alignment with spaces:** do not pad with spaces so similar clauses line up vertically — that only works in monospace. Avoid patterns like:

```haskell
fun argument = ...
fun _        = ...
```

- **Use indentation instead:** break lines and nest with consistent indentation (typically two spaces per level). Short lines may stay on one row; longer constructs wrap with deeper nesting:

```haskell
data AST binder sig n where
  -- Short line, fits fully
  Var :: Name n -> AST binder sig n
  -- Longer line, requires line breaks with nesting
  Node
    :: sig (ScopedAST binder sig n) (AST binder sig n)
    -> AST binder sig n
```

**Multiline function types** — follow the patterns in the library source:

Without constraints (`buildCache`):

```haskell
buildCache
  :: String
  -> (String -> [SomeScopeWithAST binder sig])
  -> LSP (SomeScopeWithAST binder sig) ()
```

With constraints (`findNarrowest`):

```haskell
findNarrowest ::
  ( Bifoldable sig
  , RangedSig sig
  , CoSinkable binder
  , FoldablePat binder
  , Distinct n )
  => Position
  -> AST binder sig n
  -> Maybe
      ( Either (SomePattern binder sig, SomeAST binder sig)
               (SomeAST binder sig)
      )
```

When a constrained signature still exceeds 80 characters, break the result type across lines with the same `=>`-body indentation as the argument types.

### Snippet size and exposition

Avoid large code blocks — they look bulky and bury the argument. Prefer prose for the logic, idea, and purpose of each step; use **small, focused snippets** only where a concrete example clarifies or anchors the explanation.

- Explain *what* happens and *why* in English first; show code second (or inline a few lines mid-sentence when that suffices).
- One snippet, one idea: a type signature, a single function clause, one record field group, one handler wiring step — not whole modules or long contiguous excerpts.
- Trim boilerplate, imports, and unrelated context from snippets; the reader should see the minimum needed to understand the point.
- When a flow has several steps, walk through them in prose and attach a short snippet per step rather than one monolithic listing.

## Writing Style vs. Russian Paper

| Russian paper (`.cursor/als_ru.md`) | Thesis (chapters 3–4) |
|---|---|
| Concise, skips explanations | Clear, neutral, full, factual, technical, unambiguous |
| Global overview | Deeper analysis; may be verbose where depth is needed |
| Single “implementation” section | Split into methodology vs. implementation |

Do not mirror the paper's brevity in the thesis. Expand rationale, trade-offs, edge cases, and step-by-step algorithm descriptions.

## Thesis prose and LaTeX

The thesis should read as a formal academic document, not a web article or blog post.

- **Do not use `\emph`.** Italic inline emphasis reads as rhetorical highlighting and lowers the tone. State the point in plain prose instead.
- When introducing a term, define it once in context; do not rely on emphasis to mark it as important on every mention.
- Reserve visual distinction for code (`\texttt{...}`), defined concepts on first use if the document class requires it, and standard structural elements (section titles, captions)—not for mid-sentence stress.
- When revising existing text, replace `\emph{...}` with neutral wording or, where the content is genuinely a name or identifier, `\texttt{...}`.

## Chapter Roles

**Chapter 3 — Methodology** (`chapters/chapter3.tex`):
- Broad overview of design space: requirements, alternatives, problems, trade-offs
- Discuss options considered (including rejected ones) and why
- Type classes, algorithms, and architecture at the conceptual level
- Evaluation criteria and complexity analysis where relevant

**Chapter 4 — Implementation** (`chapters/chapter4.tex`):
- Final solutions as they appear in the `free-foil-ls` library modules
- Real-world problems not obvious from theory alone (e.g. parallel scope collisions, `OffsetScope` vs. position-based binder lookup, var-wrapper nodes for go-to-definition)
- Concrete modules, handlers, cache design, and integration details
- A **dedicated subsection** for the example language server: introduce it as an external consumer of the library (not part of the library), explain what extra pieces it adds (parser, type classes for a concrete language, `main`), then describe the integration at a high level

## Examples from Flan

When illustrating library usage, mine `flan-language-server/src/LanguageServer/AgnosticLanguageServerFlan.hs` for patterns, but **do not quote or walk through the full Flan implementation** in the main implementation narrative. Instead (see also **Snippet size and exposition** above):

- Distill **minimal, self-contained snippets** that show one idea at a time (e.g. a `LSConfiguration` record, one type-class instance, one handler wiring step)
- Simplify names and trim unrelated boilerplate where it aids clarity
- Reserve the full Flan walkthrough for the example subsection; even there, prefer selective excerpts over large contiguous blocks

Keep methodology and implementation distinct: Chapter 3 explores *what could be done and why*; Chapter 4 documents *what was built and how*.
